If **Timer::read_ms()** is called repeatedly then at apprx (2^32)/2000 milli-secs (about 36 mins) the timer value jumps to (2^32)*1999/2000 and then continues from there, and wraps as normal. Each time it reaches the 1st value above, the jump occurs. Additionally, **read_us()** doesnâ€™t seem to suffer from the same problem.

```
void main() {

    Timer timer1;

    uint32_t timer_old = 0;

    timer1.reset();
    timer1.start();

    timer_old = timer1.read_ms(); // init

    while(1) {

        // Calculate timer difference since last iteration
        uint32_t timer_now = timer1.read_ms();
        uint32_t timer_delta  = timer_now - timer_old;

        pc.printf("%u %u\n", timer_now, timer_delta);

        // Check timer delta not too big
        if(timer_delta > 500u) {
            // Should never get here as loop time should always be less than 500ms

            pc.printf("*** delta error now=%u old=%u delta=%u ratio=%.2f\n", 
                timer_now, timer_old, timer_delta, 
                ((float)timer_now)/timer_old);

            while(pc.readable()) pc.getc(); pc.getc(); // flush, then pause on error
        } // if

        timer_old = timer_now; // update old

    } // while

} // main
```

I2C correction (F1, F2, F4, L1):

```
// Wait the STOP condition has been previously correctly sent
// This timeout can be avoid in some specific cases by simply clearing the STOP bit
timeout = FLAG_TIMEOUT;
while ((i2c->CR1 & I2C_CR1_STOP) == I2C_CR1_STOP) {
    if ((timeout--) == 0) {
        return 1;
    }
}

// Generate the START condition
i2c->CR1 |= I2C_CR1_START;
```

